<text>html{border: 0px #006699 solid;border-left-width: 15px} body {margin: 15px;padding: 0px;background-color:#ffffff;color:black; font-family:helvetica;font-size: 14px;line-height: 1.4em} div.volume-title {font-size:24pt;text-align:center;font-weight:bold} div.title {font-style:italic;font-weight:bold} div.mathics {font-size:larger;font-weight:bold} span.mathics-zbl {float:right} div.matverw {font-size:smaller} div.review {margin:5mm 5mm 5mm 5mm} div.aunot {font-weight:bold} div.published {font-weight:bold} .number {font-style: italic; text-align:right} div.reviewer{font-style:italic;text-align:right} EN 94C10 DNF; CNF; math1 ; Horn functions; formula size serial article Hellerstein, Lisa; Kletenik, Devorah Number: 6109928 On the gap between math2 and math3 . 2013 Summary: Given a Boolean function math4 , the quantity math5 denotes the largest set of assignments that falsify math6 , no two of which falsify a common implicate of math7 . Although math8 is clearly a lower bound on math9 (the minimum number of clauses in a CNF formula for math10 ), C̆epek et al. showed it is not, in general, a tight lower bound [6]. They gave examples of functions math11 for which there is a small gap between math12 and math13 . We demonstrate significantly larger gaps. We show that the gap can be exponential in math14 for arbitrary Boolean functions, and math15 for Horn functions, where math16 is the number of variables of math17 . We also introduce a natural extension of the quantity math18 , which we call math19 , which is the largest set of assignments, no math20 of which falsify a common implicate of math21 .</text>
